Expectation and context: capital is redrawing its map in global real estate

For years, offices were one of the great symbols of institutional real estate. Corporate towers in the main financial districts of Europe and the United States concentrated much of the capital of funds, insurers and large fortunes. However, the market is changing at an accelerating pace.

According to recent data from CBRE, institutional capital is shifting strongly toward assets linked to real estate infrastructure: logistics platforms, distribution centers, automated warehouses, connectivity hubs and assets associated with e-commerce and supply chains. What barely a decade ago was considered a secondary segment of real estate is now beginning to compete directly with traditional offices for the interest of large investors.

The phenomenon does not arise by chance. The digitalization of the economy, the structural growth of e-commerce and the need for faster and more resilient logistics chains have transformed physical infrastructure into a strategic asset. Every online order, every 24-hour delivery and every distribution network requires square meters, connectivity and operational capacity. And that is where capital is finding new opportunities.

The change also reflects a cultural and business transformation. Hybrid remote work has reduced demand for certain traditional offices, especially those that are less efficient or poorly located. Meanwhile, logistics assets show high occupancy, long-term contracts and growing demand driven by international operators.

Markets such as Madrid, Barcelona, Frankfurt, Rotterdam and Milan are seeing how logistics platforms and distribution nodes gain prominence over historically dominant segments of corporate real estate. For many institutional investors, the priority is no longer solely to own emblematic buildings, but to control the infrastructure that sustains the daily functioning of the European digital economy.

The feeling in the market mixes urgency and anticipation. Some funds are accelerating acquisitions ahead of further valuation increases, while others are trying to reposition portfolios overly exposed to traditional offices. Capital moves fast when it identifies a structural change, and that is generating growing competition for the best logistics assets in Europe.

Expected impact: infrastructure, resilience and pressure on prices

Institutional interest in this type of asset is raising valuations and reducing the availability of premium opportunities. Sector analysts believe that well-positioned logistics assets could maintain strong upward pressure on rents and prices over the coming years, especially in regions with land constraints or high operational demand.

Proximity to large cities and transport corridors has become a critical factor. Delivery speed is no longer merely a commercial advantage: it is a competitive requirement. As a result, urban warehouses, last-mile platforms and distribution centers close to consumption hubs are attracting growing attention from international capital.

At the same time, this migration toward real estate infrastructure is redefining diversification strategies. Funds that historically concentrated exposure in offices or retail are incorporating logistics, data centers and operational assets linked to connectivity and supply. The goal is to build portfolios that are more resilient to economic changes and consumption transformations.

For the investor, understanding this transition is increasingly important. The European real estate market no longer moves solely on residential location or traditional corporate demand; it now also depends on logistics flows, digital infrastructure and operational efficiency. Identifying which cities and assets benefit from these trends can make relevant differences in long-term returns and stability.

However, the increase in interest also raises the complexity of the analysis. The fragmentation of platforms, metrics and opportunities makes it difficult to compare projects in a homogeneous way, especially in an environment where institutional capital acts with speed and privileged access to information.

What it means for the investor: simplified access in an increasingly competitive market

